@node intro "[1.0] Introduction   -  What is InfoBoot?"

   InfoBoot is a CLI/Shell utility ideal for hard drive/floppy disk users
that want to make sure their machine is ticking over properly and no one is
sneaking onto their machine.
   InfoBoot will display system information (optionally at bootup).

   This is a short list detailing some of InfoBoot's features....

         °  Display the date in a more 'humane' fashion, i.e.
               Thursday, 13th February 1997.

         °  Display the time in both 24 hour and 12 hour formats.

         °  Display how much 'total' memory you have free.

         °  Display what...display you have!


@endnode

@node require "[1.1] Requirements   -  InfoBoot needs..."

   InfoBoot requires an Amiga with the following minimum specifications...

      °  Workbench/Kickstart 2.04
      °  64k free memory (maybe less!)
      °  S:InfoBoot/DATA correctly installed

   Fairly simple, and works on the vast majority of platforms as well!


@endnode

@node install "[1.2] Installation   -  Installing InfoBoot"

   To Install InfoBoot I strongly recommend using the provided 'Install'
script as it will do ALL the operations needed automaticly and is very user
freindly/configurable.
   The 'Install' script requires the 'Installer' program, supplied with
Workbench 2.04 and above. If you do not have this, check with your local PD
distributer or the Aminet.

   Manual Installation:
      (Are you mad?)
          > Copy InfoBoot <directory>
          > Makedir S:InfoBoot
          > Copy IB/DATA S:InfoBoot/


@endnode

@node command "[2.0] Command Line Args    -  Optional Features"

   Optional features that InfoBoot has are:

         °  Help - Argument Table

         °  ? - Display Usage

   To use an optional argument:

      Type: InfoBoot ?
                        This will display the usage screen.

      Type: InfoBoot Help
                        This will display an Argument Table (args).

      Simple Eh!


@endnode

@node bootups "[2.1] Boot-up operation    -  Using InfoBoot at boot-up"

   To use InfoBoot at bootup, I personally use it before anything else has
loaded (i.e. as the very first line in S:Startup-sequence).

   1) Edit S:User-startup or S:Startup-sequence
         add the line:
               <path>InfoBoot


@endnode

